        <subsection>
            <title>Using Lists</title>
            <introduction>
                <p><pubtitle>Sound Writing</pubtitle> relies heavily on lists to convey content to the reader in an organized, aesthetically pleasing way. To reap the beneifits from this decision, it is important to adhere to the principles for what <em>kinds</em> of lists should be used in which scenarios, as well as how they should be formatted.</p>
            </introduction>
            <subsubsection>
                <title>Providing Guidelines, Strategies, or Rules</title>
                <introduction>
                    <p>Perhaps the most common use of lists in the handbook is to give the reader consolidated instructions about <em>what</em> to do or <em>how</em> to do something (it is a writing handbook, after all). Often, you will want to also explain <em>why</em> to do something, so the list structure must be flexibile enough to accomodate both long explanations and brief pointers about what the reader should do. You may, in your journey of authorship of the handbook, discover that you want your particular set of instructions to look different, but <alert>readers benefit from consistency</alert>. If you think that instructions in general should be formatted differently, you should update how lists look <em>everywhere</em>, and you should update these instructions.</p>
                </introduction>
                <list xml:id="list-authoring-principles-strategies">
                    <title>Strategies for Providing Strategies in <pubtitle>Sound Writing</pubtitle></title>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p><em>Use a <c>&lt;list&gt;</c> as the outermost container for your set of instructions.</em></p>
                            <p>This tag is known as a <q>named list</q>, and can be cross<ndash/>referenced, given titles, and used to store description lists, ordered lists, and unordered lists alike. Read more about <url href="https://pretextbook.org/doc/author-guide/html/topic-lists.html">lists</url> from the <pretext/> Author's Guide.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><em>Give your list a title, <q>Strategies for <fillin/></q> where the blank is a gerund phrase like <q>providing strategies in <pubtitle>Sound Writing</pubtitle>.</q></em></p>
                            <p>This consistency alerts readers right away to what kind of content they are about ot read.</p>
                            <p>
                                <note>
                                    <p>The choice of the term <q>strategies</q> as opposed to <q>guidelines</q> or <q>rules</q> is intentional<mdash/><pubtitle>Sound Writing</pubtitle> is authored primarily by students and is meant to be informative and reliable without being authoritative. Its goal is to explain norms that really impact writing, for better and for worse, without putting them on a pedestal as a moral good. The term <q>strategies</q> achieves this end because it leaves the reader with the agency to decide whether they want to employ each strategy depending on whether they want to achieve the outcome it leads to or not.</p>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><em>Use an unordered list (<c>&lt;ul&gt;</c>) unless the order of the steps matters.</em></p>
                            <p>Unfortunately, doing this makes it impossible to cross<ndash/>reference individual items from your list, so you will have to reference the entire list if you wish to remind readers of a strategy that is elsewhere in the handbook. Treat this as a productive constraint and keep the focus of your strategies narrow and specific.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><em>Make the first sentence of each list item an <em>imperative</em> instruction<mdash/>it must be something that readers can <em>DO</em>, not just a fact.</em></p>
                            <p>You can accomplish this by wrapping the instruction in both emphasis (<c>&lt;em&gt;</c>) and a paragraph block (<c>&lt;p&gt;</c>). Subsequent explanation that clarifies the instruction should be placed in a separate paragraph block so that there is a clear visual distinction between the imperative and the explanation.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </list>
            </subsubsection>
